  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_320778141" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/320778141" />
    <a title="Andrew" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/442654-andrew"><img alt="Andrew" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1513093267p2/442654.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/320778141?book_show_action=true">Apr 29, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Andrew" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Andrew" href="/user/show/442654-andrew">Andrew</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/442654-andrew?shelf=history">history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/442654-andrew?shelf=american-studies">american-studies</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer320778141" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9913311002550590252">Hofstadter&apos;s main problem, as far as I can tell, is that he doesn&apos;t have a working definition for intellectual. At some points, he&apos;s more than happy to include artists and writers in the camp of &quot;the intellectual,&quot; but at other times, he only refers to those intellectuals working within a specifically positivist tradition. This makes a great deal of sense given the time in which the book was written, but comes off as a bit preposterous today. This, to me, makes me question the work as a text in </span>
  <span id="freeText9913311002550590252" style="display:none">Hofstadter's main problem, as far as I can tell, is that he doesn't have a working definition for intellectual. At some points, he's more than happy to include artists and writers in the camp of "the intellectual," but at other times, he only refers to those intellectuals working within a specifically positivist tradition. This makes a great deal of sense given the time in which the book was written, but comes off as a bit preposterous today. This, to me, makes me question the work as a text in the history of ideas.<br /><br />But all of that being said, it's an entertaining romp through the history of my home country's idiocies. Back then, the Tea Partiers were called Birchers. And it turns out they had more than a few antecedents. Jerks.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9913311002550590252" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


